{"title_page": "Big Little Lies (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Big Little Lies\n| image                = Big Little Lies Logo.png\n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Drama]]\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n* [[Dark comedy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/big-little-lies-review-1214695 |title='Big Little Lies' Season 2: TV Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Daniel |last=Fienberg |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| creator              = [[David E. Kelley]]\n| based_on             = {{based on|''[[Big Little Lies (novel)|Big Little Lies]]''|[[Liane Moriarty]]}}\n| writer               = David E. Kelley\n| director             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n* [[Andrea Arnold]]\n}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Reese Witherspoon]]\n* [[Nicole Kidman]]\n* [[Shailene Woodley]]\n* [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]]\n* [[Zo\u00eb Kravitz]]\n* [[James Tupper]]\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]]\n* [[Laura Dern]]\n* [[Kathryn Newton]]\n* [[Iain Armitage]]\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \"Cold Little Heart\" by [[Michael Kiwanuka]] \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 2\n| num_episodes         = 14\n| list_episodes        = #Episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* David E. Kelley\n* Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n* Reese Witherspoon\n* [[Bruna Papandrea]]\n* Nicole Kidman\n* Per Saari\n* [[Gregg Fienberg]]\n* [[Nathan Ross]]\n* Andrea Arnold\n* Liane Moriarty\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Barbara A. Hall\n* David Auge\n}}\n| location             = [[Monterey, California]]\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Yves B\u00e9langer (cinematographer)|Yves B\u00e9langer]]\n* [[Jim Frohna]]\n}}\n| editor               = \n| camera               = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime              = 45\u201358 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hello Sunshine (company)|Hello Sunshine]]\n* [[Blossom Films]]\n* David E. Kelley Productions\n* Crazyrose (season 2)\n}}\n| distributor          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n}}\n| network              = [[HBO]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format         = [[5.1 surround sound|5.1 surround]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2017|2|19}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2019|7|21}}\n| website              = http://www.hbo.com/big-little-lies/\n| website_title        = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''Big Little Lies''''' is an American [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] television series based on the novel [[Big Little Lies (novel)|of the same name]] by [[Liane Moriarty]]. Created by [[David E. Kelley]], it premiered on [[HBO]] on February 19, 2017. The seven-episode first season was written by Kelley and directed by [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]. Despite being originally billed as a [[miniseries]], HBO renewed the series for a second season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/12/08/big-little-lies-season-2-director/ |title=Big Little Lies renewed for season 2 with new director |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> Production on the second season began in March 2018 and it premiered on June 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tvline.com/2019/02/08/big-little-lies-season-2-premiere-date-hbo/ |title=Big Little Lies Sets Season 2 Premiere at HBO \u2014 The Ladies Plot in New Photos |work=TVLine |first=Dave |last=Nemetz |date=February 8, 2019 |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"S2PremiereDate\">{{cite news |url=https://tvline.com/2019/04/14/big-little-lies-season-2-premiere-date-trailer-video-hbo/ |title=Big Little Lies Gets Season 2 Premiere Date, First Trailer \u2014 Watch |work=TVLine |first=Rebecca |last=Iannucci |date=April 14, 2019 |accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> All seven episodes were written by Kelley and directed by [[Andrea Arnold]].<ref name=\"S2Episodes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/big-little-lies-season-2-scoop-whos-returning/ |title='Big Little Lies' Season 2 Scoop: HBO Reveals Who's Returning, New Character Details |work=Us Weekly |first=Emily |last=Longeretta |date=February 16, 2018 |accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Big Little Lies'' stars [[Reese Witherspoon]], [[Nicole Kidman]], [[Shailene Woodley]], [[Laura Dern]], and [[Zo\u00eb Kravitz]], and tells the story of five women in [[Monterey, California]] who become embroiled in a murder investigation. [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]], [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]], [[James Tupper]], [[Jeffrey Nordling]], [[Kathryn Newton]], and [[Iain Armitage]] feature in supporting roles. [[Meryl Streep]] joined the main cast for the second season.\n\nThe series has received critical acclaim, particularly for its writing, directing, acting, cinematography, and soundtrack. Its first season received 16 [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations and won eight, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Limited Series|Outstanding Limited Series]] and acting awards for Kidman, Skarsg\u00e5rd, and Dern. The trio also won [[Golden Globe Awards]] in addition to a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Miniseries or Television Film]] win for the series. Kidman and Skarsg\u00e5rd also received [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s for their performances.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n<!-- Credit order per Manual of Style guidelines -->\n* [[Reese Witherspoon]] as Madeline Mackenzie\n* [[Nicole Kidman]] as Celeste Wright\n* [[Shailene Woodley]] as Jane Chapman\n* [[Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd]] as Perry Wright, Celeste's husband\n* [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] as Ed Mackenzie, Madeline's husband\n* [[Zo\u00eb Kravitz]] as Bonnie Carlson, Nathan's wife\n* [[James Tupper]] as Nathan Carlson, Madeline's ex-husband and Bonnie's husband\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]] as Gordon Klein, Renata's husband\n* [[Laura Dern]] as Renata Klein\n* [[Kathryn Newton]] as Abigail Carlson, Madeline and Nathan's daughter (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Iain Armitage]] as Ziggy Chapman, Jane's son (season 2, recurring season 1)\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Mary Louise Wright, Perry's mother (season 2)\n\n===Recurring===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Darby Camp]] as Chloe Mackenzie, Madeline and Ed's daughter\n* Cameron Crovetti as Josh Wright, Celeste and Perry's son\n* Nicholas Crovetti as Max Wright, Celeste and Perry's son\n* Chloe Coleman as Skye Carlson, Bonnie and Nathan's daughter\n* [[Ivy George]] as Amabella Klein, Renata and Gordon's daughter\n* [[Merrin Dungey]] as Detective Adrienne Quinlan\n* [[Robin Weigert]] as Dr. Amanda Reisman, Perry and Celeste's therapist\n* [[P. J. Byrne]] as Warren Nippal, the principal of Otter Bay Elementary\n* [[Santiago Cabrera]] as Joseph Bachman, a theater director\n* [[Sarah Sokolovic]] as Tori Bachman, Joseph's wife\n* [[Kelen Coleman]] as Harper Stimson\n* [[Larry Sullivan]] as Oren\n* [[Gia Carides]] as Melissa\n* Larry Bates as Stu\n* [[Sarah Baker]] as Thea Cunningham (season 1)\n* [[Kathreen Khavari]] as Samantha (season 1)\n* [[Sarah Burns]] as Gabrielle (season 1)\n* [[Hong Chau]] as Jackie (season 1)\n* [[David Monahan]] as Bernard (season 1)\n* [[Molly Hagan]] as Dr. Moriarty, Ziggy's child psychologist (season 1)\n* Virginia Kull as Ms. Barnes, the children's elementary school teacher (season 1)\n* [[Joseph Cross (actor)|Joseph Cross]] as Tom, Madeline and Celeste's favorite caf\u00e9 owner (season 1)\n* [[Douglas Smith (actor)|Douglas Smith]] as Corey Brockfield, Jane's love interest and co-worker at [[Monterey Bay Aquarium]] (season 2)\n* [[Mo McRae]] as Michael Perkins, a new second-grade teacher at Otter Bay Elementary (season 2)\n* [[Crystal R. Fox|Crystal Fox]] as Elizabeth Howard, Bonnie's mother (season 2)\n* [[Martin Donovan]] as Martin Howard, Bonnie's father (season 2)\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]] as Katie Richmond, Celeste's lawyer (season 2)\n* [[Denis O'Hare]] as Ira Farber, Mary Louise's lawyer (season 2)\n* [[Becky Ann Baker]] as Marylin Cipriani, the judge in Celeste and Mary Louise's custody case (season 2)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| caption = Overview of ''Big Little Lies''\n| color1     = #F1659B\n| link1      = #Season 1 (2017)\n| episodes1  = 7\n| start1     = {{Start date|2017|2|19}} \n| end1       = {{End date|2017|4|2}}\n\n| color2     = #94C1B7\n| link2      = #Season 2 (2019)\n| episodes2  = 7\n| start2     = {{Start date|2019|6|9}}\n| end2       = {{End date|2019|7|21}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2017)===\n{{Episode table |background=#F1659B |overall=5 |caption=''Big Little Lies'' season 1 episodes |season=5 |title=23 |director=14 |writer=28 |airdate=14 |viewers=11 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = Somebody's Dead\n |DirectedBy = [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n |WrittenBy = [[David E. Kelley]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|19}}\n |Viewers = 1.13<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-feb-19-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: 'The Walking Dead' leads, 'Big Little Lies' has OK premiere |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |last=Porter |first=Rick |date=February 22, 2017 |accessdate=February 22, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = At a public school in [[Monterey, California]], a murder suddenly occurs on trivia night, but neither the victim nor the murderer is revealed. Backtracking to the first day of school, the families of five first-graders are introduced. Madeline Martha Mackenzie is a strong-willed, wealthy, and feared [[Alpha (ethology)|alpha female]] in town with a first-grade daughter and teenage daughter from an earlier marriage. Secrets are revealed, including that Madeline is struggling to cope with her ex-husband Nathan's marriage to a yoga instructor named Bonnie and also trying to build a relationship with her older daughter. Her friend, Celeste Wright, is a retired lawyer and the mother of twin sons who are also beginning at the same school. New to town is Jane Chapman \u2013 a young single mother raising her son, Ziggy. Madeline and Celeste befriend Jane. The equally wealthy and feared Renata Klein's daughter Amabella accuses Ziggy of attempting to choke her, which he denies. Celeste appears to have a very happy life with her husband Perry, but he starts to show signs of being violent. Jane's motives for moving to Monterey are unknown.\n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Serious Mothering\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|2|26}}\n |Viewers = 0.56<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-2-26-2017.html |title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 2.26.2017 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |accessdate=February 28, 2017 |work=Showbuzz Daily |date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Perry lashes out at Celeste when he discovers he missed orientation at the school, but she lets it slide. Jane looks for work with little success, and Madeline goes on the warpath against Renata when it is revealed Renata did not invite Ziggy to Amabella's birthday party. Ed questions Madeline's devotion to him when she continues to complain about seeing Nathan with Bonnie all the time, and Madeline is further disturbed when Bonnie takes Abigail, Madeline's oldest daughter, to [[Planned Parenthood]]. Nathan tries to come to a peaceful resolution with Ed about their parenting of Abigail, but Ed senses Nathan trying to intimidate him and stands firm. Madeline's younger daughter, Chloe, and Bonnie's daughter, Skye, attempt to mend the wounds between Ziggy and Amabella but it leads to an incident of unwanted affection and the parents of the four children are called into the principal's office, leading Jane to have a flashback of an unwanted episode.\n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = Living the Dream\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|5}}\n |Viewers = 1.04<ref name=\"1.03\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-march-5-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: 'Walking Dead' at lowest point since Season 2, 'Feud' has decent premiere for FX |work=TV by the Numbers |last=Porter |first=Rick |date=March 7, 2017 |accessdate=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Perry chokes Celeste when he believes she deliberately left him out of a family gathering, after which Celeste threatens to leave him. Renata's party for Amabella is a huge success but she is ultimately upset when Madeline invited Amabella's closest friends and Ziggy to [[Disney on Ice]] on the same day. At therapy, Perry claims his outbursts are out of fear that Celeste does not love him, which Celeste attempts to deny. When Abigail's academic performance begins to decline, her guidance counselor suggests it is being caused by stress at home, so she decides to live with Nathan, much to Madeline's dismay. Jane gets Ziggy involved with more extracurricular activities and helps him construct a family tree for school with Madeline's help. However, Jane opposes Ziggy\u2019s insistence upon putting his father's name on the tree, and she ultimately confides to Madeline that Ziggy was the result of rape by a man named Saxon Banks, whom she has not seen since.\n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Push Comes to Shove\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|12}}\n |Viewers = 1.04<ref name=\"1.04\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-12-2017.html |title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.12.2017 |work=[[Showbuzz Daily]] |first=Mitch |last=Metcalf |date=March 16, 2017 |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Abigail moves in with Nathan and Bonnie. Celeste legally represents Joseph and Madeline in a meeting with the Mayor regarding the controversial ''[[Avenue Q]]'', and successfully persuades the Mayor to allow the play to proceed. In the process, Celeste realizes her desire to return to work. She asks her therapist how to best convince Perry but Dr. Reisman is more concerned with why she is afraid to do so. At home, Perry tells Celeste not to attend any future meetings. When she refuses, he grabs her by the throat but quickly relinquishes when one of their boys enters the room. Joseph and Madeline kiss and it is revealed they had an affair a year ago. Madeline locates a man online whom she believes to be Saxon Banks. She informs Jane and Celeste, and they plan to travel to [[San Luis Obispo]] to confront him. Ms. Barnes, the teacher, suspects Amabella is still being bullied. Despite Amabella's assertions that she and Ziggy are friends, Ms. Barnes requests Jane to have Ziggy psychologically evaluated, but the psychologist believes that Ziggy is innocent and that he may actually be being bullied himself. \n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = Once Bitten\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|19}}\n |Viewers = 1.17<ref name=\"1.05\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-march-19-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: 'Into the Badlands' returns lower, but also higher |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=March 21, 2017 |accessdate=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Nathan spots Jane at the gun range and tells Madeline. Although Jane reassures Madeline that she carries a gun solely for its psychological benefits, Madeline begins to regret tracking down Saxon Baker, the man whom she believes to be Saxon Banks. Renata discovers a bite mark on Amabella's arm, but Amabella refuses to disclose who bit her. Renata assumes it is Ziggy and a meeting is held between Jane and the school principal. Joseph is convinced Madeline still has feelings for him but she maintains that their affair is over. While they argue, a teenage distracted driver crashes into their car. Madeline is uninjured, while Joseph is hospitalized. The incident raises suspicion from Ed and Joseph's wife, Tori. Perry is angered when Celeste does not ask the twins to tidy their toys. A confrontation triggers further violence from Perry, followed by aggressive sex. Later, Dr. Reisman confronts Celeste with the belief that she is being abused; Celeste eventually reveals that she has previously feared for her life and had considered leaving Perry. Dr. Reisman urges her to do so. Jane secretly travels to San Luis Obispo to confront Saxon Baker, taking her gun with her.\n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Burning Love\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|3|26}}\n |Viewers = 1.39<ref name=\"1.06\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-march-26-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: 'Big Little Lies' hits season high, 'Into the Badlands' improves |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Jane reveals to Madeline that she went to confront Saxon Baker, who turned out to be the wrong man. Madeline attempts to convince Jane to give up the search. Ms. Barnes relays to Jane that a petition has begun to have Ziggy suspended. Although Renata did not start it, Jane confronts her and accidentally gouges her eye. She later apologizes, realizing that they both want to protect their children. Renata forgives Jane and reveals her plan to schedule play-dates with each of Amabella's classmates to discover who is hurting her. Celeste's therapist advises her to prepare to leave Perry by renting an apartment and disclosing the abuse to friends. Later, Perry tries to initiate sex with Celeste, who defensively fractures his penis with a tennis racket. Returning from the hospital, Perry tells Celeste that she is \"lucky\" that he did not kill her. The following day she begins looking for an apartment. At the opening night of ''Avenue Q'', Tori confronts Madeline about having an affair with Joseph. At home, Madeline and Ed have another argument about her lack of passion toward him, which culminates in her alluding to having made a \"terrible mistake\". Bonnie tells Nathan that Abigail's \"secret project\" is [[Virginity auction|auctioning her virginity]] to raise money for [[Amnesty International]]. At their couples dinner, the two reluctantly tell Madeline and Ed. Madeline furiously confronts Abigail, disclosing her affair in the process. \n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = You Get What You Need\n |DirectedBy = Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n |WrittenBy = David E. Kelley\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|4|2}}\n |Viewers = 1.86<ref name=\"1.07\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/sunday-cable-ratings-april-2-2017/ |title=Sunday cable ratings: 'The Walking Dead' finale lowest since Season 2 |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=April 4, 2017 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Following another beating, Celeste decides to leave Perry the day after trivia night. Ziggy confesses to Jane that it was Max, one of Celeste's sons, who choked Amabella. Madeline talks to Joseph about his wife knowing about their affair, and Jane woefully tells Celeste that her son is the bully. Celeste realizes that Max was emulating Perry\u2019s abuse, having overheard it while he was playing a video game. When preparing to leave for trivia night, Perry sees a text message on Celeste's phone from the landlady of her new apartment. He confronts her on the way to the party, but is interrupted by Renata. At the party, Celeste tells Renata that Max is the bully and Amabella framed Ziggy out of fear of Max. Meanwhile, a drunk Madeline runs away during Ed's singing performance after realizing just how much he loves her and how little she gives him in return. Jane goes after her and finds her atop stairs at the back of the venue. Madeline tells Jane that she cheated on Ed. Renata also goes after them and apologizes to Jane for having blamed Ziggy. Celeste joins the women, followed by Perry. Bonnie follows them and watches the group from afar. Jane sees Perry and realizes that he is Saxon Banks. Perry pleads with Celeste to come back home with him and when she declines, he viciously attacks her. The group unsuccessfully fights Perry off until Bonnie rushes in and pushes him down the stairs, killing him. In police interviews, the women confirm that there was a fight with Perry but claim he fell accidentally. Later, the five women and their children lounge at the beach, where Detective Quinlan continues to watch them.\n |LineColor = F1659B\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background=#94C1B7 |caption=''Big Little Lies'' season 2 episodes |overall=5 |season=5 |title=23 |director=14 |writer=28 |airdate=14 |viewers=11 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = What Have They Done?\n |DirectedBy = [[Andrea Arnold]]\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=[[David E. Kelley]]|s=David E. Kelley and [[Liane Moriarty]]|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|6|9}}\n |Viewers = 1.42<ref name=\"2.01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-9-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.9.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=June 11, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In the aftermath of Perry's death, Celeste, Madeline, Jane, and Renata try to move on with their lives, while Bonnie considers turning herself in to the police. It is the first day of second grade for the children, and the five women reunite. Perry's mother, Mary Louise, who is staying with Celeste, begins asking questions about her son's death, and clashes with Madeline. Nathan worries about how distant Bonnie has been with him and asks Ed for help. Abigail decides she will not go to college, to Madeline's disapproval. At the beach, Corey, a co-worker of Jane's, asks her if she is one of the \"Monterey Five\". Jane tells the other women (apart from Bonnie) about this, and Renata assures them that the police have nothing. Celeste has nightmares about Perry and Mary Louise questions her about them.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Tell-Tale Hearts\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|6|16}}\n |Viewers = 1.47<ref name=\"2.02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-16-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.16.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=June 18, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Celeste crashes her car while on [[Ambien]], with no recollections of what happened. A worried Nathan calls Bonnie's parents to town. Gordon is arrested for [[insider trading]] and [[stock fraud]] by the [[FBI]]. Renata is dumbfounded that he is playing with an expensive train set while he has lost all of their money. Mary Louise finds out about Ziggy's parentage from Max and Josh. She refuses to believe that Perry raped Jane by [[victim blaming]] her. Madeline grounds Chloe after finding out that she told Max, Josh, and Ziggy that the three boys share the same father. Jane reluctantly tells Ziggy about how he is the product of a rape. Ed discovers Madeline's infidelity.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = The End of the World\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|6|23}}\n |Viewers = 1.62<ref name=\"2.03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-23-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.23.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=June 25, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Bonnie clashes with her mother, and remembers traumatic incidents from her childhood. Amabella has an anxiety attack during a lesson about [[climate change]]. Renata hires a child psychologist and finds out Amabella is worried about the planet dying, her father going to jail as well as Renata's mental state. Renata blames Gordon for it and confronts Principal Nippal and Mr. Perkins about teaching second graders about climate change. Mary Louise approaches Jane at work and requests for a paternity test be done, which Jane refuses. Mary Louise then lurks in the parking lot of Jane's apartment to take a look at Ziggy. She finds similarities between Ziggy and Perry's twin brother, who died as a child, but refuses to accept the fact that Perry was abusive and a rapist. To save their marriage, Madeline and Ed visit Celeste's therapist. During a parents meeting at Otter Bay Elementary, Madeline breaks down while speaking. Jane and Corey go on a date, but she is unable to be intimate with him.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = She Knows\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|6|30}}\n |Viewers = 1.61<ref name=\"2.04\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-30-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 6.30.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=July 2, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = During a pumpkin carving party at Madeline's house, Mary Louise turns up uninvited. Mary Louise gets an apartment in the same building as Jane, which Celeste deems overstepping her boundaries. When Mary Louise subtly insinuates that Perry was womanizing to seek refuge from Celeste, Celeste slaps her. The next day, over coffee with Celeste, Mary Louise admits her husband left her after the death of Perry's brother and that she deserved the blame. Mary Louise approaches lawyer Ira Farber to gain custody of her grandchildren, citing negligence by Celeste. Madeline and Ed's marriage continues to deteriorate. Renata and Gordon have a disastrous bankruptcy hearing when she refuses to cooperate. At Amabella's birthday party, Jane tells Corey about her rape and Bonnie's mother has a stroke after seeing a vision of Bonnie drowning.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = Kill Me\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|7|7}}\n |Viewers = 1.77<ref name=\"2.05\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-7-7-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 7.7.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=July 10, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Celeste refuses a settlement offer from Mary Louise\u2019s lawyer for joint custody of the boys, and the case goes to trial. Renata tries to get Mary Louise to drop the case, who in turn taunts her for being a working mother. Ziggy is bullied by a boy, who calls him a mistake and that his father is a rapist; Max and Josh defend him and the three of them beat up the bully, leading to their suspension. Jane tries to be intimate with Corey but the trauma causes her to break down. Celeste, Jane, Corey and the three boys go on a kayak trip during their suspension, while Renata and Amabella make use of this opportunity to bond as mother and daughter at the pool. Ed and Madeline go to couples therapy, where Madeline promises that she will not make the same mistakes again. Later, Tori hits on Ed at a bar, with Joseph staring at them from a nearby table. At the hospital, Bonnie's mother asks her to pull the plug. A distraught Bonnie once again considers turning herself in to the police, but on her way to a police station spots Corey leaving it.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = The Bad Mother\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|7|14}}\n |Viewers = 1.63<ref name=\"2.06\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-7-14-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 7.14.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=July 16, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Celeste and Mary Louise go to trial to battle for the custody of Max and Josh. Celeste is completely shocked and hurt when Mary Louise's lawyer asks her a wide array of personal questions. Celeste explains that she is coping with grief and intends to improve herself and get better. Just before the judge announces the verdict, Celeste interrupts to say that Mary Louise never took the stand and that isn't fair. Celeste herself wants to question Mary Louise and the judge agrees. Ed meets with Tori, who comes on to him and tells him that she has fantasized about him. Madeline approaches Ed again and says that she wants to try to work it out. Jane questions Corey about his presence at the police station and he tells her that he was just called in for questioning by the detective, who asked him if Jane has ever talked with him about the night Perry died. Corey claims that he told the detective nothing. Though mildly reassured, Jane stops answering his calls and texts because she says she isn't ready for something new just yet. Bonnie confesses everything (including pushing Perry and her resentment towards her mother) to her mom, while she is in a coma. as she thinks her mother is going to die soon and that this may be her last chance to say anything.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = I Want to Know\n |DirectedBy = Andrea Arnold\n |WrittenBy = {{StoryTeleplay|t=David E. Kelley|s=David E. Kelley and Liane Moriarty|tfirst=y}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|7|21}}\n |Viewers = 1.98<ref name=\"2.07\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-7-21-2019.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 7.21.2019|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=July 23, 2019|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Mary Louise is questioned in court by Celeste, where Mary Louise is asked about Perry's brother's death and how he coped and how she treated him. Later Celeste shows a video that her son took of Perry physically abusing her, and claims that Mary Louise would raise her own sons to be similar abusers. Celeste ends up with full custody, and Mary Louise leaves Monterey Bay. Bonnie tells her mother she loves her just before she dies and tells Nathan she doesn't love him. Ed and Madeline renew their vows. Jane and Corey progress in their relationship with Ziggy's approval. Gordon arranges to keep his train set despite the repossession of their other property, to the disapproval of Renata who furiously destroys it and leaves him. Finally, Bonnie texts the rest of the Monterey Five that she is going to confess, in response to which all four women accompany her to the police station.\n |LineColor = 94C1B7\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn August 6, 2014, it was announced [[Nicole Kidman]] and [[Reese Witherspoon]] had optioned the screen rights to [[Liane Moriarty]]'s novel ''Big Little Lies''. The actresses were expected to develop the project as a film in which they would both star. Bruna Papandrea and Per Saari were set to executive produce alongside Kidman and Witherspoon. Moriarty was also expected to produce as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleming Jr |first1=Mike |title=Nicole Kidman, Reese Witherspoon Team On 'Big Little Lies' Rights Deal |url=https://deadline.com/2014/08/nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-team-on-big-little-lies-rights-deal-815273/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=August 6, 2014}}</ref> On November 25, 2014, it was announced that Kidman and Witherspoon had decided to develop the project into a limited television series instead of the originally planned film. Additionally, it was announced that television series would be written by [[David E. Kelley]].<ref name=\"FilmAnnouncement\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Nicole Kidman & Reese Witherspoon To Star In 'Big Little Lies' Limited Series, Penned By David E. Kelley |url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-star-big-little-lies-limited-series-david-e-kelley-1201296852/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=November 25, 2014}}</ref> On May 8, 2015, it was announced that HBO had given the production a series order and that in addition to writing, Kelley would also executive produce.<ref name=\"SeriesAnnouncement\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title='Big Little Lies' Limited Series Starring Nicole Kidman & Reese Witherspoon Picked Up By HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/big-little-lies-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-hbo-limited-series-1201423026/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=May 8, 2015}}</ref> On October 23, 2015, it was reported that [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] was in talks to direct the first episode of the series with the potential to direct more.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleming Jr |first1=Mike |title=Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e In Talks To Helm HBO's 'Big Little Lies' With Nicole Kidman, Reese Witherspoon |url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/jean-marc-vallee-big-little-lies-hbo-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-david-e-kelley-1201592401/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=October 23, 2015}}</ref> On December 17, 2015, it was announced that Vall\u00e9e would direct all seven episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e To Direct All 7 Episodes Of HBO's 'Big Little Lies' |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/jean-marc-vallee-direct-all-episodes-hbo-big-little-lies-1201668906/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=December 17, 2015}}</ref> On November 28, 2016, it was announced that the series would premiere on February 19, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies' From David E. Kelley Gets Premiere Date On HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/big-little-lies-premiere-date-hbo-liane-moriarty-david-e-kelley-reese-witherspoon-1201860563/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |date=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe show was initially conceived of and billed as a miniseries{{r|moreau20190226}} of seven episodes. In the wake of the Emmy nominations, Reese Witherspoon said: \"As of right now, I think it's pretty whole. I feel really good about where it is, and if this is all it ever was, it's a beautiful thing we all accomplished together\",<ref name=\"breakrules\"/> while Vall\u00e9e came out strongly against the idea of producing a second season: \"There's no reason to make a season two. That was meant to be a one-time deal, and it's finishing in a way where it's for the audience to imagine what can happen. If we do a season two, we'll break that beautiful thing and spoil it\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/04/big-little-lies-director-jean-marc-vallee-on-the-finale.html |title=Big Little Lies Director Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e on Why the Finale Gala Was the Toughest Shoot of His Career |website=Vulture |first=Maria Elena |last=Fernandez |date=April 3, 2017 |accessdate=November 23, 2017}}</ref> Later, when the show garnered an array of critical accolades, he changed his mind: \"It'd be great to reunite the team and to do it. Are we going to be able to do it, altogether? I wish.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/09/17/big-little-lies-season-2-hbo-jean-marc-vallee-emmys-2017/ |title=Big Little Lies Director Does About-Face on a Possible Season 2: 'It'd Be Great' |website=[[TVLine]] |first=Dave |last=Nemetz |date=September 17, 2017 |accessdate=November 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Second season===\nIn July 2017, two weeks after the series was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Limited Series]], HBO revealed that a second season was possible, and that Moriarty had been asked to write a story for it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/07/26/big-little-lies-hbo-season-2-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon/ |title=Big Little Lies: HBO Boss Confirms Season 2 in Early Development |website=[[TVLine]] |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=July 26, 2017 |accessdate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, after the [[Critics' Choice Television Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination voting periods were over,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/tv-shows/big-little-lies-season-2-angry/ |title=Here's why Season 2 of \"Big Little Lies\" is already making people angry |website=Hello Giggles |first=Natalia |last=Lusinski |date=December 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref> HBO officially renewed the series for a seven-episode second season to be written by Kelley, directed by [[Andrea Arnold]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/12/08/big-little-lies-renewed-season-2-hbo-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon/ |title=Big Little Lies Officially Returning for Season 2; Kidman, Witherspoon to Star |website=[[TVLine]] |first=Dave |last=Nemetz |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref> and based on a new novella by Moriarty.<ref name=\"moreau20190226\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/big-little-lies-season-two-what-to-know-1203150485/ |title=Everything You Need to Know About 'Big Little Lies' Season 2 |last=Moreau |first=Jordan |date=February 26, 2019 |work=Variety |access-date=March 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Vall\u00e9e remains an executive producer of the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsweek.com/big-little-lies-jean-marc-vallee-director-742938 |title='Big Little Lies' gets season 2, despite director Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e once saying it never would |work=Newsweek |first=Anna |last=Menta |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Meryl Streep]] joined the cast as the mother of Alexander Skarsg\u00e5rd's character.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/jan/24/meryl-streep-to-star-in-big-little-lies-season-two |title=Meryl Streep to star in Big Little Lies season two |work=The Guardian |date=January 24, 2018 |accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe announcement of the second season, and\u2014specifically\u2014its timing, enraged the producers of rival shows that were competing for award nominations in the limited series category, particularly since the announcement was made after voting for the [[Critics' Choice Television Award|Critics' Choice Awards]] and [[Golden Globe Awards]] had ended. The [[Producers Guild of America]] restarted voting for the 2018 [[PGA Awards]], reclassifying the show from a limited series to a [[drama series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/big-little-lies-moved-limited-series-to-drama-series-category-pga-awards-hbo-renewal-1202223387/ |title='Big Little Lies' moved from Limited Series to Drama Series category by PGA Awards following HBO renewal |work=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/big-littles-lies-sequel-announcement-sparks-outrage-awards-categorization-1065999 |title='Big Little Lies' sequel announcement sparks outrage about its awards categorization |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Scott |last=Feinberg |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, it was reported by ''[[IndieWire]]'' that director Andrea Arnold lost creative control after filming had completed, and it was given to season 1 director Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e in an attempt to unify the style between the seasons. Arnold was initially promised by HBO that the show would be done in her vision, including post-production, and was unaware that Vall\u00e9e would edit the footage she had shot. Once Vall\u00e9e completed his work on ''[[Sharp Objects (miniseries)|Sharp Objects]]'', he took over the editing process along with his own editorial team in Montreal. HBO also ordered 17 more days of additional photography, to be filmed by Arnold, but were overseen by Vall\u00e9e. Significant reworking of the episodes also took place, where episodes were shortened.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/big-little-lies-season-2-andrea-arnold-lost-creative-control-jean-marc-vallee-1202156884/ |title='Big Little Lies' Season 2 Turmoil: Inside Andrea Arnold's Loss of Creative Control |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Chris |last=O'Falt |date=July 12, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref> In response, HBO programming president Casey Bloys stated, \"There's a lot of misinformation around that subject\" and \"the director typically does not have final creative control\". Bloys clarified that Vall\u00e9e came back to \"hone the episodes\" after being asked by the entire producing team, including Reese Witherspoon and Nicole Kidman, and that they were clear with Arnold about how the process would work from the start.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/07/24/big-little-lies-season-2-controversy-andrea-arnold-hbo/ |title=Big Little Lies: HBO Boss Responds to Reports of Behind-the-Scenes Drama |website=[[TVLine]] |first=Dave |last=Nemetz |date=July 24, 2019 |accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Future===\nHBO president Casey Bloys said a third season of the show was \"not realistic\" due to scheduling the show's actors. However, Bloys mentioned that HBO is more than willing to greenlight a third season if the cast are able to work out their schedules.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/07/11/big-little-lies-season-3-renewed-returning/ |title=Big Little Lies Season 3: Will It Happen? |website=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=July 11, 2019 |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n====Season 1====\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 360\n| footer = [[Reese Witherspoon]] (left), [[Nicole Kidman]] (middle) and [[Shailene Woodley]] (right) star in ''Big Little Lies''.\n\n| image1 = Reese Witherspoon at TIFF 2014.jpg\n| image2 = Nicole Kidman Cannes 2017 2.jpg\n| image3 = Shailene Woodley March 18, 2014 (cropped).jpg\n}}\nAlongside the initial announcement of the production's development, it was reported that Kidman and Witherspoon would also star in the adaptation.<ref name=\"FilmAnnouncement\"/><ref name=\"SeriesAnnouncement\"/> In December 2015, it was announced that [[Shailene Woodley]], [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]], [[Laura Dern]], and [[Zo\u00eb Kravitz]] had joined the cast in lead roles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Greg |title=Shailene Woodley To Join 'Big Little Lies,' Says Nicole Kidman |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/shailene-woodley-big-little-lies-nicole-kidman-1201653900/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=December 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title=Adam Scott to Co-Star in HBO's Reese Witherspoon, Nicole Kidman Drama (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/adam-scott-star-hbos-reese-847232 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |language=en |date=December 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=Laura Dern Set For HBO's 'Big Little Lies' |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/laura-dern-cast-hbo-big-little-lies-shailene-woodley-nicole-kidman-1201663330/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=December 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Zo\u00eb Kravitz Joins HBO's 'Big Little Lies' |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/zoe-kravitz-cast-big-little-lies-hbo-1201665011/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=December 11, 2015}}</ref> On January 5, 2016, it was announced that [[Alexander Skarsgard]] and [[James Tupper]] had joined the main cast and that [[Jeffrey Nordling]], [[Santiago Cabrera]], [[P. J. Byrne]], [[Kelen Coleman]], [[Sarah Burns]], [[Darby Camp]], Cameron and Nicholas Crovetti, [[Ivy George]], Chloe Coleman, Virginia Kull, [[Sarah Baker]], [[Kathreen Khavari]], Larry Bates, [[Hong Chau]], and [[Gia Carides]] had joined the show's supporting cast.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=Alexander Skarsgard, James Tupper & More Join Nicole Kidman & Reese Witherspoon in HBO's 'Big Little Lies' |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/alexander-skarsgard-james-tupper-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-big-little-lies-1201676452/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=January 5, 2016}}</ref> A few days later, it was reported that [[Iain Armitage]] had joined the cast in the role of Woodley's character's son.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pint-Sized Theater Critic Iain Armitage to Appear Opposite Shailene Woodley in HBO's BIG LITTLE LIES |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Pint-Sized-Theater-Critic-Iain-Armitage-to-Star-Opposite-Shailiene-Woodley-in-HBOs-BIG-LITTLE-LIES-20160108 |website=Broadway World |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |language=en |date=January 8, 2016}}</ref> Soon after that, it was reported that Merrin Dungey, Larry Sullivan, and David Monahan had also joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': Merrin Dungey, Larry Sullivan, David Monahan Join Cast Of HBO Limited Series |url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/big-little-lies-cast-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-hbo-limited-series-merrin-dungey-1201680340/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=January 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\nOn January 24, 2018, it was announced that [[Meryl Streep]] had joined the main cast in the role of Mary Louise Wright, the mother of Perry (played by Alexander Skarsgard in Season 1).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title='Big Little Lies': Meryl Streep Joins Season 2 Cast Of HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/big-little-lies-meryl-streep-season-2-cast-hbo-series-nicole-kidman-reese-witherspoon-1202268349/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |date=January 24, 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, it was confirmed that Shailene Woodley, Laura Dern, Zo\u00eb Kravitz, Adam Scott, James Tupper, Jeffrey Nordling and Iain Armitage were returning for the second season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': Shailene Woodley, Laura Dern & Zo\u00eb Kravitz Confirmed For Season 2 Return |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/big-little-lies-shailene-woodley-laura-dern-zoe-kravitz-confirmed-return-season-2-1202291918/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |date=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': Adam Scott Confirmed For Season 2 Return |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/big-little-lies-adam-scott-confirmed-season-2-return-1202305129/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |date=February 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': James Tupper, Jeffrey Nordling & Iain Armitage Set Season 2 Return |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/big-little-lies-james-tupper-jeffrey-nordling-iain-armitage-season-2-return-1202305890/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |date=February 28, 2018}}</ref> On March 27, 2018, it was announced that [[Douglas Smith (actor)|Douglas Smith]] had joined the cast in a recurring role.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': Douglas Smith Joins Season 2 Cast Of HBO Drama |url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/big-little-lies-douglas-smith-season-2-cast-hbo-drama-1202354189/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 27, 2018 |date=March 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ivie |first1=Devon |title=Big Little Lies Has Cast a Sexy Surfer Character for Season 2 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/03/big-little-lies-casting-douglas-smith-joins-as-sexy-surfer.html |website=Vulture |accessdate=March 27, 2018 |language=en |date=March 27, 2018}}</ref> On April 3, 2018, it was confirmed that Kathryn Newton, Robin Weigert, Merrin Dungey, and Sarah Sokolovic were returning for the second season. Newton and Sokolovic have been upped from recurring roles to series regulars. Additionally, it was announced that Crystal Fox had joined the cast in a main role and that Mo McRae would appear in a recurring capacity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title='Big Little Lies' Closes Deals For 4 To Return; Adds Two New Season 2 Cast Members|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/big-little-lies-kathyrn-newton-robin-weigart-merrin-dungey-return-crystal-fox-sarah-sokolovic-mo-mcrae-season-2-1202357749/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=April 3, 2018|date=April 3, 2018}}</ref> On April 10, 2018, it was announced that [[Martin Donovan]] had been cast in a recurring role.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title='Big Little Lies' Books Martin Donovan for Key Role (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/big-little-lies-books-martin-donovan-key-role-1101230|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 10, 2018|language=en|date=April 10, 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, it was reported that [[Poorna Jagannathan]] had joined the cast in a recurring capacity. Additionally, it was confirmed that [[P.J. Byrne]] would reprise his role of Principal Nippal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title='Big Little Lies': Poorna Jagannathan Set To Recur In Season 2 Of HBO Series|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/big-little-lies-poorna-jagannathan-recur-season-2-hbo-series-1202384095/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 8, 2018|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title='Big Little Lies': P.J. Byrne Set For Season 2 Return|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/big-little-lies-p-j-byrne-season-2-return-reprise-principal-nippal-1202397743/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=May 25, 2018|date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> On June 15, 2018, it was announced that [[Denis O'Hare]] had been cast in a recurring role.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='Big Little Lies': Denis O'Hare Set To Recur In Season 2 Of HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/big-little-lies-denis-ohare-recur-season-2-hbo-series-1202411550/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 15, 2018 |date=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe series was shot with an [[Arri Alexa]] digital camera. Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e, who directed the entirety of the first season, preferred using natural lighting and handheld shooting style to allow actors to move freely around the set.<ref name=\"breakrules\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/08/big-little-lies-nicole-kidman-jean-marc-vallee-alexander-skarsgard-hbo-emmys-1201863905/ |title=How 'Big Little Lies' broke the rules to lead its Emmy rivals |website=IndieWire |first=Anne |last=Thompson |date=August 7, 2017 |accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the series was filmed on location on the [[Monterey Peninsula]] and [[Big Sur]]. Several scenes were shot in [[Pacific Grove, California|Pacific Grove]] and [[Carmel Highlands]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cntraveller.com/gallery/where-is-big-little-lies-filmed/ |title=Where 'Big Little Lies' is filmed |website=[[CN Traveler]] |first=James |last=Medd |accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\nA soundtrack for the series was released on [[Google Play]] and [[iTunes]] on March 31, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://play.google.com/store/music/album/Various_Artists_Big_Little_Lies_Music_From_The_HBO?id=Btkwcp4ihdfzudizc2svndgltoe |title=Big Little Lies (Music From the HBO Limited Series) |accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Broadcast===\nOn February 7, 2017, the series held its official premiere at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jensen |first1=Erin |title=Reese Witherspoon, daughter Ava Phillippe are twins at 'Big Little Lies' premiere |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/02/08/big-little-lies-premiere-reese-witherspoon-ava-phillippe-kathreen-khavari/97637918/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |language=en |date=February 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Porreca |first1=Brian |title='Big Little Lies' Premiere: Cast Talks Murder Mystery, TV's Portrayal of Women |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/big-little-lies-premiere-reese-witherspoon-shailene-woodley-nicole-kidman-interviews-97334 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |language=en |date=February 8, 2017}}</ref> Internationally, the series premiered on February 20, 2017, in Australia on [[Showcase (Australian TV channel)|Showcase]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2017/02/airdate-big-little-lies.html |title=Airdate: Big Little Lies |date=February 1, 2017 |accessdate=February 2, 2017 |work=TV Tonight |first=David |last=Knox}}</ref> and on March 13, 2017, in the United Kingdom and Ireland on [[Sky Atlantic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/14/big-little-lies-review-reese-witherspoon-nicole-kidman-someone-dead |title=Big Little Lies review: someone's going to end up dead \u2013 but who? |date=March 14, 2017 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nOn October 16, 2016, HBO released the first teaser trailer for the series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lincoln |first1=Ross A. |title='Big Little Lies' Teaser: Someone's Papa Was A Rollin' Stone |url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/hbo-big-little-lies-first-teaser-1201837276/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=October 16, 2016}}</ref> On December 5, 2016, HBO released a full length trailer for the series.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Greg |title='Big Little Lies' Trailer: Watch HBO's Murderous Moms Of Monterey |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/big-little-lies-trailer-hbo-reese-witherspoon-nicole-kidman-1201864974/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=March 15, 2018 |date=December 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe first season was released on Blu-ray and DVD on August 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Big-Little-Lies-Press-Release/23257 |title=Big Little Lies \u2013 Official HBO Press Release and Package Art for DVDs, Blu-rays |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=May 1, 2017 |accessdate=July 18, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707223809/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Big-Little-Lies-Press-Release/23257 |archivedate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> The second season was released on January 7, 2020, on DVD and manufacture-on-demand Blu-ray by [[Warner Home Entertainment]] and [[Warner Archive Collection]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/BIG-LITTLE-LIES-Season-2-Comes-to-DVD-Jan-7-20191107 |title=BIG LITTLE LIES Season 2 Comes to DVD Jan. 7 |publisher=Broadway World |date=November 7, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|+Aggregated reviews for ''Big Little Lies''\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#F1659B;\" |\n| 1\n| 93% (124 reviews)\n| 75 (42 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#94c1b7;\" |\n| 2\n| 85% (101 reviews)\n| 82 (36 reviews)\n|-\n|}\nThe first season of ''Big Little Lies'' was met with a positive response from critics. On the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season holds a 93% \"certified fresh\" rating with an average rating of 8.05 out of 10 based on 124 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Bitingly funny and highly addictive, ''Big Little Lies'' is a twisty, thrilling, enlightening ride led by a first-rate cast.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/big_little_lies/s01/ |title=Big Little Lies: Season 1 |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the first season a score of 75 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/big-little-lies/season-1 |title=Big Little Lies: Season 1 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine listed ''Big Little Lies'' as one of its top ten television shows of 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last=D'Addario |first=Daniel |url=http://time.com/5037916/top-10-tv-shows-2017/ |title=The Top 10 Television Shows of 2017 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=November 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe second season has received critical acclaim. On Rotten Tomatoes, the season holds an 85% \"certified fresh\" rating with an average rating of 7.71 out of 10 based on 101 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Gorgeous and gripping, ''Big Little Lies''{{'}} second season doubles down on the dark humor and gives its impressive cast even more juicy drama to chew on \u2013 especially an excellent Meryl Streep.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/big_little_lies/s02/ |title=Big Little Lies: Season 2 |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=June 2, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the season has a score of 82 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/big-little-lies/season-2 |title=Big Little Lies: Season 2 |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref> Ben Travers of ''[[IndieWire]]'' wrote a positive review giving it a \"B+\" grade, concluding that Season 2 is a \"wholly different beast\" and \"doesn\u2019t feel like a necessary addition so much as an enjoyable epilogue\", yet it is \"still very, very good\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/big-little-lies-season-2-review-hbo-1202146117/ |title='Big Little Lies' Review: Season 2 Is Very Different and Very Good |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Ben |last=Travers |date=May 31, 2019 |accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n====Season 1====\n{{Television episode ratings\n| noshare  = y\n|caption = ''Big Little Lies'' season 1 ratings\n| title1   = [[#ep1|Somebody's Dead]]\n| date1    = February 19, 2017\n| rs1      = 0.3\n| viewers1 = 1.13<ref name=\"1.01\"/>\n| dvr1     = 0.3\n| dvrv1    = n/a\n| total1   = 0.6<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/dvr-ratings/taboo-triples-in-adults-18-49-cable-live-7-ratings-for-feb-13-19/ |title='Taboo' triples in adults 18\u201349: Cable Live +7 ratings for Feb. 13\u201319 |last=Porter |first=Rick |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=March 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n| totalv1  = n/a\n\n| title2   = [[#ep2|Serious Mothering]]\n| date2    = February 26, 2017\n| rs2      = 0.2\n| viewers2 = 0.56<ref name=\"1.02\"/>\n| dvr2     = 0.3\n| dvrv2    = 0.84\n| total2   = 0.5\n| totalv2  = 1.39<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/dvr-ratings/cable-live-7-ratings-for-feb-20-26-2017 |title='The Walking Dead' makes its lead even bigger in cable Live +7 ratings for Feb. 20\u201326 |last=Porter |first=Rick |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n| title3   = [[#ep3|Living the Dream]]\n| date3    = March 5, 2017\n| rs3      = 0.4\n| viewers3 = 1.04<ref name=\"1.03\"/>\n| dvr3     = n/a\n| dvrv3    = n/a\n| total3   = n/a\n| totalv3  = n/a\n\n| title4   = [[#ep4|Push Comes to Shove]]\n| date4    = March 12, 2017\n| rs4      = 0.4\n| viewers4 = 1.04<ref name=\"